					<description><![CDATA[Dear James,

That post resonates so much with me. I had to learn this the hard way. Growing up with a value system that only who works himself to near death is a worthy human being, I never respected my boundaries for years. Last year I hit bottom rock after an extremely stressful working period of 5 weeks. Project was done and time for celebration had come, but instead the only thing I managed was to lie down in my bed with the blanket up to my nose, freezing, weak, and totally burned out. For one solid week I could do nothing else than stare at the ceiling while I had the feeling of being surrounded by cold, heavy, grey fog, like a heavy blanket of grey mass coming down upon me.

This has been the most horrid experience in my life and I never ever want to return to this point. I&#039;m still struggling with my old behavioural pattern but this experience has taught me to refrain from responsibilities I don&#039;t want to have and to say &#039;no&#039;. The thing I&#039;ve learned is that a valuable and responsible human being first takes care of herself in order to do good work and in order to not let others down (like they teach us in the airplane before take-off. ;) ).]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Dear James,</p>
<p>That post resonates so much with me. I had to learn this the hard way. Growing up with a value system that only who works himself to near death is a worthy human being, I never respected my boundaries for years. Last year I hit bottom rock after an extremely stressful working period of 5 weeks. Project was done and time for celebration had come, but instead the only thing I managed was to lie down in my bed with the blanket up to my nose, freezing, weak, and totally burned out. For one solid week I could do nothing else than stare at the ceiling while I had the feeling of being surrounded by cold, heavy, grey fog, like a heavy blanket of grey mass coming down upon me.</p>
<p>This has been the most horrid experience in my life and I never ever want to return to this point. I&#8217;m still struggling with my old behavioural pattern but this experience has taught me to refrain from responsibilities I don&#8217;t want to have and to say &#8216;no&#8217;. The thing I&#8217;ve learned is that a valuable and responsible human being first takes care of herself in order to do good work and in order to not let others down (like they teach us in the airplane before take-off. ;) ).</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
